{{redirect-distinguish|Germophobia|Germanophobia}} {{for|the hatred of sound|Misophonia}}
'''Mysophobia''', also known as '''verminophobia''', '''germophobia''', '''germaphobia''', '''bacillophobia''' and '''bacteriophobia''', is a [[pathological fear]] of contamination and [[Microorganism|germs]]. The term was coined by [[William A. Hammond]] in 1879 when describing a case of [[obsessive–compulsive disorder]] (OCD) exhibited in repeatedly washing one's hands.<ref name="Hammond">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RrbqCbV5xvMC|title=Neurological Contributions|first=William Alexander|last=Hammond|date=1879|page=40|publisher=Putnam|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Mysophobia has long been related to compulsive [[hand washing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webmd.com/mental-health/features/cleanliness-rules-germaphobes-lives|title=Cleanliness Rules Germaphobes' Lives|website=WebMD|accessdate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Names pertaining directly to the abnormal fear of dirt and filth include molysmophobia or molysomophobia, rhypophobia, and rupophobia, whereas the terms bacillophobia and bacteriophobia specifically refer to the fear of [[bacteria]] and [[microbes]] in general.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phobiasource.com/bacillophobia-fear-of-microbes/ |title=Bacillophobia – Fear of microbes |accessdate=September 3, 2014}}{{unreliable source|date=December 2014}}</ref>
The term ''mysophobia'' comes from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] μύσος (''musos''), "uncleanness"<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dmu%2Fsos1 μύσος], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref> and φόβος (''phobos''), "fear".<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dfo%2Fbos φόβος], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', on Perseus</ref>
